The following steps should be completed in <code>dom0</code> for {{project_name_long}}. <ref>
Debian has enabled AppArmor by default since the <code>buster</code> release, but Fedora has not. This matters because Qubes is Fedora-based and therefore uses the <code>dom0</code> (not VM) kernel by default. Therefore this step is still required even though {{project_name_long}} is based on a recent enough Debian version.
</ref> After these settings are applied to the {{project_name_long}} template, the {{project_name_long}} (App Qube) will inherit the AppArmor kernel settings. 
It is unnecessary to recreate the {{project_name_gateway_vm}} App Qubes to benefit from the new kernel parameters. <ref>[https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/issues/1091 Since Qubes R3.0, App Qubes inherit the kernelopts setting of their Template].</ref> It is also important to verify AppArmor is active in the <code>{{project_name_long}}</code> VM after making these changes.

=== {{project_name_workstation_long}} ===
{{Box|text=
'''1.''' Open a <code>dom0</code> terminal.

<code>Qubes App Launcher (blue/grey "Q")</code> &rarr; <code>System Tools</code> &rarr; <code>Xfce Terminal
</code>

'''2.''' List the current kernel parameters.

{{CodeSelect|code=
qvm-prefs -g {{project_name_workstation_template}} kernelopts
}}

Qubes R4 and later releases will show.<br />

{{Code2|nopat}}

'''3.''' Keep the existing kernel parameters and add <code>apparmor=1 security=apparmor</code>. 

For example.

{{CodeSelect|code=
qvm-prefs -s {{project_name_workstation_template}} kernelopts "nopat apparmor=1 security=apparmor"
}}

'''4.''' List the current kernel parameters again (hit the up arrow key twice; it is unnecessary to type the command again).

{{CodeSelect|code=
qvm-prefs -g {{project_name_workstation_template}} kernelopts
}}

The output should show AppArmor is part of the new kernel parameters. For example.<br />

''nopat apparmor=1 security=apparmor''

'''5.''' Start the <code>{{project_name_workstation_vm}}</code> App Qube and confirm AppArmor is now active.

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo aa-status --enabled ; echo $?
}}

The output should show.<br />

{{Code2|0}}
}}